INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (1,1,'Mr WordPress','','http://wordpress.org/','','2013-10-27 19:41:47','2013-10-27 19:41:47','Hi, this is a comment.\nTo delete a comment, just log in and view the post&#039;s comments. There you will have the option to edit or delete them.',0,'post-trashed','','',0,0),(219,126,'Ulcelfbrelowl','molinakalina@gmail.com','','91.207.6.86','2012-01-25 07:37:10','2012-01-25 07:37:10','Hello! Just want to say thank you for this interesting article! =) Peace, Joy.',0,'1','','',0,0),(376,199,'Karl The Big Mean Bunny','kjnilsson@gmail.com','','194.110.203.172','2011-10-07 09:05:47','2011-10-07 09:05:47','No more wrapping a timer? :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(557,334,'Erik Forbes','erikforbes@gmail.com','http://brightumbra.wordpress.com/','149.32.192.35','2012-01-12 14:58:17','2012-01-12 14:58:17','Great post - this is exactly the sort of thing I\'m looking for to build a project I\'ve had in mind for a while. Talk about good timing! =)',0,'1','','',0,0),(558,334,'Donny V','donnyv@gmail.com','','68.45.188.48','2012-08-19 11:43:37','2012-08-19 11:43:37','Nice and simple tutorial and easy to read. Thanks!',0,'1','','',0,0),(688,397,'Tony Bruce','tony.bruce@tonybruceconsulting.co.uk','http://dancedwiththetester.blogspot.com/','62.7.66.38','2012-01-19 13:57:22','2012-01-19 13:57:22','Good overview.\n\nThought I\'d add:\n\nPrime Directive - Rather than ask if everybody agrees (cause who would say no?) you could ask that everyone read it out loud, they may not currently believe it but over time they may/will/could/should.\n\nEven if one or two people do say no it doesn\'t make sense to me to stop the Retrospective, you\'ll get more value out of running it.\n\nI\'d also add that some kind of <a href=\"http://www.hodu.com/safety-check.shtml\" rel=\"nofollow\">safety check</a> is a good idea.\n\nThere are a few books around to get some other ideas, I recommend starting with these:\n\n<a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Agile-Retrospectives-Making-Pragmatic-Programmers/dp/0977616649/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1326981182&amp;sr=1-1\" rel=\"nofollow\">Agile Retrospectives: Making Good Teams Great</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.alibris.com/search/books/qwork/7740688/used/Project%20Retrospectives\" rel=\"nofollow\">Project Retrospectives</a>',0,'1','','',0,0),(727,448,'Five Blogs – 27 March 2012 &laquo; 5blogs','','http://5blogs.wordpress.com/2012/03/27/five-blogs-27-march-2012/','74.200.244.122','2012-03-27 12:00:49','2012-03-27 12:00:49','[...] Writing maintainable unit tests Written by: Andrew Jutton [...]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(728,448,'Dennis Doomen','dennis.doomen@avivasolutions.nl','http://www.dennisdoomen.net','62.45.242.156','2012-03-31 08:43:26','2012-03-31 08:43:26','Great article. The Test Data Builder is one of the best patterns I\'ve been applying since I started practicing TDD. Since you didn\'t mention the original source for that pattern, I thought I share it here.\nhttp://www.natpryce.com/articles/000714.html\n\nBy the way. If you have any feedback regarding Fluent Assertions, let me know or share it on StackOverflow here.\nhttp://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/fluent-assertions',0,'1','','',0,0),(808,451,'Vin D\'Amico','vin@damicon.com','http://brainslink.com/','173.48.246.235','2012-03-07 18:37:21','2012-03-07 18:37:21','Outstanding idea! A side benefit is the increase in communication and collaboration that takes place. Everyone develops a better understanding of how the software works and why it behaves the way it does. Learning is enhanced and the final delivery is bound to benefit.\n\nThanks for sharing.',0,'1','','',0,0),(809,451,'Darren McMillan','darren@bettertesting.co.uk','http://www.bettertesting.co.uk','135.196.96.218','2012-03-08 11:05:38','2012-03-08 11:05:38','Like many things on the tinterweb this probably has many names.  I myself call it a \"show and tell\".  I talked about it here: http://www.bettertesting.co.uk/content/?p=123\n\nI think anything that takes a proactive approach to testing is invaluable.  This itself if handled correctly I\'ve found actually builds up strong bonds between the developer and tester.  It is no longer a reactive, disapointing chat or email, you both face the challenges together and learn to improve one another.\n\nGood stuff!  Thanks for sharing.',0,'1','','',0,0),(810,451,'Sharath','sharu.b@gmail.com','http://testtotester.blogspot.com','194.9.188.21','2012-03-08 12:29:30','2012-03-08 12:29:30','Nice post Andrew. There are no doubts on the benefits of this process. We used to do something similar in our project but called it \"demo\" to the tester. The tester was encouraged to run positive tests on Dev\'s PC during the demo. But I like your term -&gt; \"Dev Box Testing\" :)\n\nThough this was an excellent feedback loop we could not keep up with it. Some reasons were\n- Testers were occupied in testing sessions when the developer wanted to move the story to testing\n- Product owners stuck in a meetings or un-available\n- 2 or more developers want to move their stories to testing\n\nBut if this process suit your context +1 from me to the idea',0,'1','','',0,0),(811,451,'Duncan Nisbet','duncan.nisbet@gmail.com','http://www.duncannisbet.co.uk','193.243.130.17','2012-03-08 14:39:51','2012-03-08 14:39:51','Nice post - thanks for sharing.\n\nTaking it one step further, we (Testers) also look at the supporting test code. This gives us a chance to help ensure the regression tests/checks are relevant - instils more faith in the CI process.\n\nAnother great advantage of dev box testing is helping the move towards the whole team approach. The Programmer/Tester pairing (more so than BA - thats a deeper conversation) helps the Tester by having a greater understanding of the code e.g. in terms of regression testing. It helps the Programmer understand how Testers think and as such help them test e.g. building testability into the code, writing automated checks which the Tester would think of that a Programmer might not normally think of.\n\nI\'m a Tester, BTW',0,'1','','',0,0),(825,485,'Franc','frankra@gmail.com','http://about.met/franc','213.121.62.3','2012-03-13 11:57:01','2012-03-13 11:57:01','I came to the same conclusions last week when I presented an intro to BDD to my team.\n\nWe\'ll hopefully use SpecFlow, any tips as to how to best share feature files with product owners?',0,'1','','',0,0),(826,485,'Paul Littlebury','pablo@jaffamonkey.co.uk','http://blog.jaffamonkey.com','158.180.192.10','2012-03-13 14:02:08','2012-03-13 14:02:08','Very timely post – BDD is coming into same firing line, as Agile, Scrum etc. And largely down to poor understanding and implementation of something that is essentially the tried and tested TDD method. As ever, it’s the implementation of a methodology that is problem. But people would rather blame process, rather than adopting the Agile/Lean review and improve approach. More fool them!',0,'1','','',0,0),(827,485,'Five Blogs – 13 March 2012 &laquo; 5blogs','','http://5blogs.wordpress.com/2012/03/13/five-blogs-13-march-2012/','216.151.210.19','2012-03-13 16:24:43','2012-03-13 16:24:43','[...] Learning from mistakes with BDD Written by: Andrew Jutton [...]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(828,485,'Andrew Jutton','ajutton@gmail.com','http://','2.217.85.9','2012-03-13 19:21:45','2012-03-13 19:21:45','Hi Franc, to be honest we don\'t let the produt owner touch the feature files. However we do let the BA\'s add the scenarios to the feature files, in fact that is our only copy of the scenarios as the code base is always the only truth. As part of our continuous integration we generate a couple of reports that specflow provides, which lists the scenarios also. This is made available to everyone in the company to access. Hope that helps',0,'1','','',825,1),(829,485,'Andrew Jutton','ajutton@gmail.com','http://','2.217.85.9','2012-03-13 19:25:26','2012-03-13 19:25:26','Thanks Paul, I quit agree. Everyone\'s trying to do the same thing, but everyone\'s trying to do it differently. Sometimes you just need to take a step back and review where you are',0,'1','','',826,1),(830,485,'Vin D\'Amico','vin@damicon.com','http://brainslink.com/','63.247.139.108','2012-03-15 16:31:09','2012-03-15 16:31:09','Good points. Anything that can go wrong, will. This applies to the business process being performed as well as the software. It\'s good practice for the team to think about human behavior. What might a novice user do? What shortcuts will an expert user take? Never assume that there is a single path through the software from the start of an activity to its conclusion.',0,'1','','',0,0),(839,591,'Ben Keeping','benjaminkeeping@gmail.com','','92.40.254.45','2012-06-29 16:19:50','2012-06-29 16:19:50','Six for me would be : Review &amp; Refactor\nThe best teams consistently review their methods and in-team processes.\nAsk questions, find the pain points, change up how you do things.\nAnd look at opportunities to refactor - try and leave the codebase in a nicer state than it was when you started. Refactor those mingin bits that always exist!',0,'1','','',0,0),(840,591,'Mark Chidlow','mark.chidlow@agileorange.com','','81.106.144.226','2012-07-01 17:21:52','2012-07-01 17:21:52','Completely agree with Andrew (and Ben) on all the above points. Though \'law\' seems a little strong perhaps ;-)\n\nPoint 1: Liking the \'don\'t write your own frameworks..\' comment. I have seen this happen so many times. Stop re-inventing the wheel! If you are looking to use an open-source framework just make sure there\'s a good active community - and of course that this is first properly discussed and agreed within the team. Focus on delivering features not frameworks.\n\nPoint 2: Good points. I\'m a stickler for consistency in all aspects of development (not just coding). Use tools such as StyleCop to police coding style. I\'d also recommend the use of a \'domain glossary\' to ensure that the same terminology/naming is used within the code (entities, business rules, namespaces etc) that is used in the business domain.\n\nPoint 3: 100% agree. It\'s easy to get attached to some code you have put a lot of thought and effort into - but as you know, come back to it a few months (or just days!) later and you\'d be refactoring it!\n\nPoint 4: In my view, sharing and collaboration is the most important point here. Also remember in multi-team environments to not only share within the team but also where appropriate share across teams.\n\nPoint 5: In my experience a team that has fun produces better code, innovates more, is willing to go that extra mile and collaborates more effectively. Fun up to a point of course - 3 hour technical discussions down the pub are fun but...\n\nPoint 6 (Ben): Regarding refactoring - this is of course a key point. Just remember to discuss any significant refactors with the rest of the team and ensure there is sufficient test coverage to catch errors in the refactor before embarking on it. Also balance the benefit of refactoring with time and effort involved. You know that you could probably refactor until the cows come home without delivering any new features. In fact I\'ve done it myself!',0,'1','','',0,0);
